1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Bb4 4.e5 b6 {From a static point of view,
this move looks good for Black; but White obtains a lot of development.}
5.Qg4 {A typical move in the Winawer Variation: Black has to
take an important decision.} Bf8 6.Bg5 {Attacking move! This
is ideal in chess.} Qd7 7.O-O-O Ne7 8.Bxe7 h5 9.Qh3 {From here
the queen controls very important squares like f5 and h5.} Bxe7 10.f4 {The
natural plan for White in this pawn structure is to play f5,
attacking the pawn chain and opening the position.} Bb7 (10...Ba6 {Is
more natural - White gets a good position after...} 11.Bxa6 Nxa6 12.Kb1
{Followed by a plan like Qe3-h3-Nf3/e2-g4-f5. The important thing
is to prepare f5.}) 11.Nf3 Nc6 12.Ng5 {Preventing Black from
castling queen side.} g6 13.Be2 Na5 14.Kb1 (14.g4 {Directly is
also possible.}) 14...a6 15.g4 h4 16.Rhf1 {Preparing f5.} b5 17.Bd3 Nc4
18.Ne2 (18.Nxf7 $5 {This sacrifice is very typical in this pawn
structure.} Kxf7 19.f5 Kg8 20.f6 Bb4 21.Bxg6 {And the "f" and
"g" pawns can now sweep forward.}) 18...Qc6 19.Ka1 {A prophylactic
move but not very necessary...} a5 20.Nxf7 $5 Kxf7 21.f5 gxf5 $2 (21...g5 $1
{Saves Black's position.} 22.fxe6+ Kg8) 22.gxf5 Rag8 23.Nf4 {Now
it's all over...} Rh6 24.Rg1 Rgh8 25.f6 Bxf6 26.exf6 Rxf6 27.Ng6 Rg8 28.Qxh4
{In this game, you should learn at least two things: 1. the typical
f4-f5 plan; 2. the typical Nxf7 sacrifice.}   1-0

