1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Bb4 4.e5 Ne7 5.a3 Bxc3+ 6.bxc3 b6 {With
the same idea we saw in the previous game: exchange the bad bishop.} 7.Qg4
{Again, the typical answer. In this case, it's a bit different
because Black no longer has his dark-squared bishop.} Ng6 (7...O-O {Is
another option; White can simply play...} 8.Bg5 {Putting pressure
on Black's position.} Qd7 9.Bd3 Ba6 10.Bxh7+ Kxh7 11.Qh4+ {Is
a trick you should take into account.} Kg8 12.Bxe7 Qa4 13.Kd2 $1 {And
White is winning due to the double threat 13. Bxf8 and 13. Bf6!!} Re8 14.Bf6 $1)
8.h4 h5 9.Qd1 (9.Qg3 {Is another alternative that looks better
at first sight; but taking a deeper look into the position, we
can understand that attacking the h5 pawn is very important here.
That's why 9.Qd1 is the move I like the most.}) 9...Ba6 10.Bxa6 Nxa6 11.Bg5
{Developing and attacking...} Qd7 12.Ne2 {Going for Ng3.} Qc6 13.O-O Ne7
14.Qd3 {Developing and attacking.} Nb8 15.Ng3 {It's time to attack
h5. You may think: "What if Black simply protects this pawn with
g6?" This is White's idea - he doesn't want to win the pawn;
the idea is to provoke g6 and then attack on the weak dark squares.} Nd7
16.Qf3 g6 {Now the objective is reached, it's time to rethink
the position. It looks like White should try to open up the position
- preparing c4 looks very logical.} 17.a4 {This move is very
useful: 1. threatens a5; 2. The a3 square can be used by the
bishop (Bc1-a3) or even by a rook.} a5 18.Rfd1 Nf5 19.Ra3 Ra7 20.Nf1 Nf8
21.Bc1 Nh7 22.g3 Kd7 $2 (22...O-O $1 {And Black is ok...}) 23.Ne3 $1 {Now
Black's position becomes desperate...} Kc8 24.c4 $1 Nxe3 25.Bxe3 Qd7 26.cxd5
exd5 27.c4 $1 Rd8 28.Rc1 dxc4 29.Rxc4 Qd5 30.Qe2 Rb7 31.Rb3 Qe6 32.Qc2 Kb8
33.Rc6 Qd5 34.e6 fxe6 35.Bf4 Ka8 36.Bxc7 Rc8 37.Rb5 Qd7 38.Rxa5+ {In
this game, you should learn at least: 1. the idea of attacking
h5 to provoke g6; 2. a typical idea in the Winawer Variation
is to open the position to take advantage of the bishop against
knight - c4 is a common way to do this.}   1-0

