1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Bb4 4.e5 c5 5.a3 Ba5 {This is a secondary
variation.} 6.b4 {The idea is unpin the knight to go to b5.} cxd4 7.Nb5
{Threatening Nd6.} Bc7 8.f4 {It's very important to support the
e5 pawn.} Ne7 9.Nf3 Bd7 10.Nxc7+ {If you understand the properties
of this pawn structure, this exchange doesn't need explanation.
The dark squares are very weak.} (10.Nbxd4 {Is a less strong
but acceptable option.}) 10...Qxc7 11.Bd3 {White doesn't hurry
to take on d4, because it's lost anyway and White can use the
time to finish his development and then maybe recapture it in
a better way.} a6 12.Bb2 Nbc6 13.O-O Rc8 14.Qe1 $1 {The queen has
excellent possibilities (f2,g3 or h4) from this square; also
defends b4 and can help to play a4.} Nf5 15.Qf2 Nce7 16.a4 $1 {Seizing
space on the queen side.} O-O (16...Ne3 $5 {It's interesting...} 17.Rfc1
N7f5 18.Nxd4 $14) 17.Nxd4 {Finally, White decides to recover the
pawn.} Nc6 18.Nxc6 Bxc6 19.b5 Bd7 20.g4 $1 Nh6 21.h3 $1 {Black's
pieces haven't played. White has optimal coordination.} Qd8 22.Bd4 {Black
has nothing to do.} axb5 {Decisive mistake: the opening of the
"a" file leaves Black with nothing to do!} 23.axb5 Rc4 24.Bxc4 dxc4 25.Rfd1
Qc8 26.Rab1 Re8 27.Bb6 {After this game, you should understand
the importance of the dark-squared bishop in this position; also
White's plan of seizing space on both flanks, leaving Black with
a cramped position.}   1-0

