1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Bb4 4.e5 c5 5.a3 Bxc3+ 6.bxc3 Qa5 {The idea
of this move is to blockade the queen side with Qa4 - the problem
is that the king side feels lonely.} 7.Bd2 Qa4 8.Qg4 $1 {Logical
move! White should attack on the king side - the c2 pawn doesn't
matter.} Kf8 9.Nf3 Ne7 (9...Qxc2 {Is also possible, but White
doesn't have any problem in getting compensation - as you can
see in the theory section.}) 10.Be2 b6 11.c4 $1 {A typical move
in the Winawer! White wants to open the position as much as he
can - for obvious reasons (king safety, bishop pair).} Ba6 (11...dxc4 12.dxc5
bxc5 13.Ng5 {With clear advantage to White.} (13.Qe4 Qc6 14.Qxc6 Nexc6 $14))
12.cxd5 Bxe2 13.d6 (13.dxe6 $5 Bc4 14.dxc5 Nbc6 {The position is
very complicated...} 15.Ng5 Nxe5 16.Qe4 N7c6 17.f4) 13...Nf5 14.Kxe2 Nc6
15.c3 cxd4 16.Qe4 $1 {White is better.} Qb5+ $2 17.c4 $1 {It's all
over.} Qa4 (17...Qxc4+ 18.Ke1 Qd5 19.Qxd5 exd5 20.g4 Nh6 21.Rc1 Nd8 22.Bxh6
gxh6 23.Nxd4) 18.g4 Nh6 19.Rhc1 Rc8 20.c5 Ke8 21.cxb6 axb6 22.Rab1 Qa6+
23.Ke1 Kd7 24.Nxd4 Nxd4 25.Qxd4 b5 26.Bxh6 gxh6 27.Qf4 Rhf8 28.Qf6 Qa5+
29.Kf1 Qd8 30.Rxc8 Kxc8 31.Qf3 Qa5 32.Qc6+ {In this game, you
should review some important ideas: open the position with c4,
attack the king side with Qg4.}   1-0

