1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nc6 7. a4 {This is a
different move order, but we are going to reach a known position.} (7. Nf3 {Is
normal, according to our repertoire.}) 7... Qa5 8. Bd2 Nge7 9. Nf3 c4 {We have
reached a normal position in the 7.Nf3 variation. White's plan is to prepare
f4-f5.} 10. g3 Bd7 11. Bh3 {According to White's plan, this bishop is good
here.} O-O-O 12. O-O Rdf8 13. Qe2 h6 14. Rfb1 {Using this file is important in
this variation} Nd8 (14... f5 {Is maybe a better try...} 15. exf6 Rxf6 16. Ne5
$14) 15. Bc1 {Also the a3-f8 diagonal is key in this variation.} Bxa4 16. Ba3
Ndc6 17. Bb4 Qa6 18. Bd6 {The position is awful for Black, and White works out
a plan that finishes it in great style!} b5 19. Nd2 $1 Kd7 20. Nb3 $1 {Great
and deep plan: very difficult to find!} cxb3 21. cxb3 Qb7 22. bxa4 b4 23. Qb5
Rb8 24. Bf1 Qb6 25. Rxb4 Rb7 {About this game, we should learn: 1. what are
the normal lines for the pieces in this variation (b1-b8, a3-f8 and sometimes
a1-a8); 2. an interesting way of taking advantage of the typical pinned bishop
on a4. (Nd2-b3).} 1-0

