1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Bb4 4.e5 c5 5.a3 Bxc3+ 6.bxc3 Ne7 7.Nf3 Bd7 8.a4 {White
should prevent Ba4.} Nbc6 9.Be2 Qa5 10.Bd2 c4 {Blocking the position
from being opened up.} 11.O-O f6 12.exf6 gxf6 13.Bf4 $1 {This move
is very strong in my opinion: White's idea is to play Bd6, and
so it isn't a very good idea to take the c3 pawn.} Ng6 (13...Qxc3 14.Bd2
Qb2 15.Rb1 Qa2 16.a5 $1 {And White's compensation is more than
enough.}) 14.Bd6 O-O-O 15.Qd2 {Now White simply defends his pawn
and has a much better position.} Rhg8 16.Rfb1 e5 17.dxe5 fxe5 18.Rb5 Qa6
{Black's queen is an awful situation; that, plus the bishop pair,
determines White's advantage.} 19.Rab1 {It's a good move, but
maybe requires a lot of calculation from a practical point of
view.} (19.g3 $5 {This is a better idea. When one side has a positional
advantage, he should simply avoid his opponent's counterplay.
In that way, the positional superiority will lead to victory
in a very simple and natural way. This move closes the "g" file
and limits Black's counterplay.}) 19...Be6 (19...Bh3 $5 20.Qh6 $1 Bxg2 21.Qxh7
Nge7 22.Bxe7 Bxf3+ 23.Kf1 {And, believe it or not, White has
good possibilities here. The thing is that evaluating this position
is really difficult: that's why I consider 19.g3!? more practical...})
20.Ng5 $1 {White is winning!} Bf5 (20...Rxd6 21.Nxe6 Rxe6 22.Bg4 Nce7 23.Rxb7 $6
{Is the simple move.} (23.Qh6 $1 {It's the complicated one!} Kb8 24.Bxe6
Qxe6 25.Rxb7+ Ka8 26.g3 $16) 23...Nf4 24.Rb8+ Kd7 25.Rxg8 Nxg8 26.g3 Nf6 27.gxf4
Nxg4 28.Qxd5+ Kc7 29.Qc5+ Kd7 30.h3 $14) 21.Nf7 {It's curtains for
Black!} Nf4 22.g3 Rd7 23.Nh6 Rxd6 24.Nxf5 Rf6 25.Ne3 Nh3+ 26.Kg2 Nf4+ 27.Kh1
Nxe2 28.Qxe2 Rgf8 29.Qg4+ Kb8 30.Rxb7+ Qxb7 31.Rxb7+ Kxb7 32.Qd7+ Ka6 33.Nxd5
Rg6 34.Nb4+ Kb6 35.Nd5+ {From this game, you should learn: 1.
the importance of the dark-squared bishop - this is important
in almost all the games; 2. the prophylactic move g3.}   1-0

